{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489420"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:15:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:15:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"653"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/653"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.42,0.23,0.05,0.28,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"653"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51777"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/653"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"653"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37077"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"496"},{"type":"tags","id":"1387"},{"type":"tags","id":"1444"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14788"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31238"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51777"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old man presents to his general practitioner with right earache of one week duration, associated with a blocked sensation and scant discharge. Examination shows an occluded right ear canal with green-grey discharge, debris, surrounding skin oedema and pain upon moving his pinna. The left ear is normal. The Weber test lateralises to the right and the Rinne test shows bone conduction greater than air conduction on the right (abnormal), with air conduction greater than bone conduction (normal) on the left.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial approach to treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ear toilet","Sofradex ear drops","Oral amoxicillin","Sofradex ear drops and oral amoxicillin","Topical acetic acid"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has otitis externa, as evidenced by the history, the findings of conductive hearing loss, and the otoscopy findings. Dry \u003Cstrong\u003Eear toileting\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial management. A dry process should be used in case there is any tympanic membrane perforation. While this patient should also be prescribed topical treatment, aural toileting maximises the efficacy of topical medications by removing wax and debris from the canal and may provide some immediate symptomatic relief. The \u003Cstrong\u003Etopical treatment\u003C/strong\u003E that could be applied after any debris and wax has been cleared from the canal may be an antibiotic combined with a steroid to reduce any inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no benefit to \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E in mild to moderate cases of otitis externa, and topical treatment should suffice. Oral antibiotics may be considered if there is evidence of extension of the infection beyond the ear canal. \u003Cstrong\u003EAcetic acid\u003C/strong\u003E is less effective as a topical treatment when compared to combination antibiotic/antiseptic/corticosteroid ear drops.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ear toilet and removal of wax debris should precede any topical antibiotic use to ensure adequate exposure of the inflamed tissues."],"references":["Kaushik V, Malik T, Saeed SR. Interventions for acute otitis externa. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2010 Jan 20;(1). Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20091565/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37077"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"653"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37077"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-28T21:35:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-28T21:36:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"653"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51777"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"r